Reasoning: The paper discusses refined versions of the Azuma-Hoeffding inequality with applications in information theory, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. Additionally, the paper includes examples related to data structures (cs.DS) and machine learning (cs.LG), which further support these sub-categories. The paper also discusses the use of concentration inequalities in computational complexity (cs.CC) and statistical inference (cs.SI), which are also possible sub-categories.
